				&lt;font face="arial" size="2"&gt;1460, 1351, 1297, 1248&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
		&lt;tr align="right"&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
				&lt;font face="arial" size="2"&gt;Complex, disulfide bis-dimer&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td&gt;
				&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td align="left"&gt;
				&lt;font face="arial" size="2"&gt;1510, 1433, 1350, 1244&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Additional evidence of true complexation of glycols to dimer thiadiazoles is shown by the interaction with the glycol as measured by simple solubility. Dimer thiadiazoles have little interaction with most solvents as seen by their saturation point in that solvent. Higher interactions would be seen by more solvation, which would be evident by higher levels dissolving (again higher interaction). The solvolysis/complexation is evidence of this higher interaction. We believe that the glycol must have the ability to coordinate with two dimer molecules to function a chain link in the complex and afford the EP properties.&lt;br /&gt;
	&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table border="0" cellpadding="4"&gt;
