					&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td valign="top" width="13%"&gt;
				&lt;p align="center"&gt;
					&lt;font face="arial" size="2"&gt;2e&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
					&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td valign="top" width="13%"&gt;
				&lt;p align="center"&gt;
					&lt;font face="arial" size="2"&gt;2e&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
					&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td valign="top" width="13%"&gt;
				&lt;p align="center"&gt;
					&lt;font face="arial" size="2"&gt;2e&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
					&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
			&lt;td valign="top" width="13%"&gt;
				&lt;p align="center"&gt;
					&lt;font face="arial" size="2"&gt;2e&lt;/font&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
					&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
			&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Results indicate that Vanlube&lt;sup&gt;&lt;font size="2"&gt;&amp;reg;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; 972 does not corrode copper but coats the metal with a film. Most of the film can be removed with acetone and a paper towel. Acetone is highly polar and coordinates well with the metal sites and still some thiadiazole coordination remains.&lt;br /&gt;
	&lt;br /&gt;
	We wished to test if this coating was &amp;quot;protective&amp;quot; to corrosion by treating the copper with lubricant with copper corrosive additive alone and compare that to the corrosive additive with the Vanlube&lt;sup&gt;&lt;font size="2"&gt;&amp;reg;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/sup&gt; 972 thiadiazole present.&lt;br /&gt;
	&lt;br /&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
