        <item>
            <guid isPermaLink="false">tag:noria.com,2010-06-10:publishing:magazines:rp:9c625a9c-5bcb-4124-8b7a-9d5e00e99a7d</guid>
            <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/motors/~3/Mcv7WtQ3jSs/Motor-tip-temperature-coefficient</link>
            <a10:author>
                <a10:name>PdMA Corporation</a10:name>
            </a10:author>
            <category>Industry News</category>
            <category>Articles</category>
            <title>Electric motor tip covers negative temperature coefficient</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	Your motor insulation has a negative temperature coefficient. This means that as the motor temperature rises, like in normal operations, the insulation resistance to current flow reduces. If insulation temperature goes down, like after a shutdown, the resistance goes up. This change can be dramatic. For every 10-degree Celsius rise in temperature, the resistance is cut in half. For every 10-degree drop in temperature, the resistance is doubled. Be careful that you are not trying to trend insulation resistance without performing a temperature correction of the readings. Performing a polarization index test during a significant temperature change will provide additional data for evaluation.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	To view a case study showing an insulation integrity problem, visit the PdMA Corporation Web site at &lt;a href="http://r20.rs6.net/tn.jsp?et=1103328734301&amp;amp;s=4679&amp;amp;e=0010em_GHpXTwcBZE1Nx0ZQbfWYA9tqCD_7rn41OySqthMIwM8jNpWwgqwccSuGqnoaABOCiexhT9aZvrdfCFCMdTAFtkm8dJxv6PyO7MkJGew=" target="_blank"&gt;http://www.pdma.com&lt;/a&gt;and click on the Insulation Fault Zone button.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/motors/~4/Mcv7WtQ3jSs" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
            <a10:updated>2010-04-20T14:10:29-05:00</a10:updated>
            <a10:content type="text/html" src="http://reliableplant.com/Read/24135/Motor-tip-temperature-coefficient" />
        <feedburner:origLink>http://reliableplant.com/Read/24135/Motor-tip-temperature-coefficient</feedburner:origLink></item>
        <item>
            <guid isPermaLink="false">tag:noria.com,2010-06-10:publishing:magazines:rp:f0e17b4d-ac1b-474e-a603-9d5e00bb3bb4</guid>
            <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/motors/~3/j-_CFRrCKEw/motors-energy-dollars</link>
            <a10:author>
                <a10:name>Baldor Electric Company</a10:name>
            </a10:author>
            <category>Web Exclusives</category>
            <category>Articles</category>
            <title>Choice in motors saves Weyerhaeuser energy dollars</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	When Weyerhaeuser, a $20 billion international forest products company, began its search for an energy-efficient motor, it faced the same issues and opportunities as other manufacturers; the rising cost of power, and the desire to take advantage of energy rebates. But what makes Weyerhaeuser different is the way in which it approached the motor selection process.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	With approximately 50,000 motors in operation, accounting for 81 percent of the company&amp;rsquo;s electrical load, it was clear that Weyerhaeuser wanted the most efficient motor available. But it also wanted a product with superior quality and reliability that would help it reduce unplanned downtime and cut maintenance costs. Deciding not to focus on the purchase price alone, the company determined that a strictly scientific approach would help it reach its ultimate goal of reducing total cost of ownership.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Weyerhaeuser selected a cross-functional team for the project and named John Holmquist, a Weyerhaeuser senior scientist and Fellow of the Institute of Electrical and Electronic Engineers, as one the team&amp;rsquo;s leaders. Holmquist and the technology team quickly decided that the IEEE 841 standard, which is recognized as a tough design and manufacturing standard for improved reliability, efficiency and performance, would become the new baseline for Weyerhaeuser motor requirements. Next, the team asked six motor manufacturers to provide samples for evaluation. Each motor was extensively tested, torn down for inspection, and then rated on more than 170 performance attributes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;
	&lt;img src=" http://media.noria.com/sites/web_exclusives/baldor101.jpg " /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Based on overall quality, efficiency and availability, the team selected the Reliance 841 XL Premium Efficient motor. It reported that the product met or exceeded all IEEE specifications, and that because it was a standard Reliance offering, the motor would be readily available from Reliance stock centers throughout the U.S. and Canada.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;I&amp;rsquo;m excited to partner with Reliance and standardize on a motor that is applicable to all parts of the Weyerhaeuser industry &amp;ndash; from forest, to wood, to pulp and paper,&amp;rdquo; said Holmquist. &amp;ldquo;The Reliance 841 XL is designed for severe-duty applications and meets all of our requirements for quality, reliability and energy efficiency.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	There were several features of the Reliance motor with which Holmquist was particularly impressed.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;Reliance really has a precision-balanced rotor providing smoother operation, reduced vibration and longer bearing life,&amp;rdquo; said Holmquist. &amp;ldquo;Additionally, using Conrad bearings with bearing isolators on each end will extend the life of the motors.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Based on payback calculations developed by the team, the Reliance 841 XL would be used in all new applications. Calling older standard motors &amp;ldquo;economically obsolete&amp;rdquo;, Holmquist told his colleagues that &amp;ldquo;it pays us to buy the new energy-efficient motor.&amp;rdquo; But the team still needed to determine what made the best economic sense when it came to the issue of failed motors and retrofitting existing motors.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The team calculated both the short- and long-term cost of repair and compared those numbers with the cost and long-term benefits of installing the new energy-efficient motor. The numbers indicated that all failed motors, 50 horsepower and lower, should be replaced with the Reliance product.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;We determined that it&amp;rsquo;s a more cost-effective solution to scrap the failed motor and replace it with the Reliance 841 XL,&amp;rdquo; said Holmquist. &amp;ldquo;We also recommended that motors 60 horsepower and higher should be evaluated on an individual basis to determine the most cost-effective solution.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	And while it may seem difficult to replace a motor that&amp;rsquo;s running, the team discovered that in many cases replacing these inefficient motors actually makes good financial sense.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;Our recommendation is that all motors that can meet a payback period of less than 3.5 years should be retrofitted,&amp;rdquo; Holmquist reported.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Theoretically, the technology team&amp;rsquo;s choice of motor and its recommendations on the motor&amp;rsquo;s usage added up to reduced operating costs. But would those numbers add up the same way on the mill floor?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;&lt;em&gt;NORPAC Puts Motors to the Test&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	Among the Weyerhaeuser mills that enthusiastically embraced the decision to standardize on the Reliance 841 XL was the North American Paper Corporation (NORPAC). The NORPAC facility, located in Longview, Wash., is a joint venture between Weyerhaeuser and Nippon Paper Industries of Japan. The mill, the second largest of its kind in North America, operates 24 hours a day, 365 days a year, producing more than 750,000 tons of high-quality newsprint annually &amp;ndash; enough to stretch to the moon and back every two weeks. NORPAC serves newspaper publishers and commercial printers in the western United States and Japan. Major newspaper groups served in the U.S. include: Gannett, Knight-Ridder, Dow Jones, San Francisco Newspaper Agency, the Oregonian and the Seattle Times.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Mill leadership readily understood how dramatically the rising cost of energy impacted their operation. Since they couldn&amp;rsquo;t control the price of electricity, they were willing to do all they could to reduce the energy that NORPAC used. In order to capture the maximum energy savings as soon as possible, plus take advantage of incentives being offered by the local utility, NORPAC began by changing out larger motors first before moving to smaller units. By fall, NORPAC had retrofitted more than 200 older-model motors with the Reliance 841 XL, reducing energy costs significantly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Today, Mark Higginson, senior support engineer for NORPAC&amp;rsquo;s electrical and control systems, continues to emphasize the energy-efficiency program.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;It&amp;rsquo;s been fun to jump on the bandwagon and keep it moving,&amp;rdquo; he says. &amp;ldquo;Our systematic approach to identify inefficient equipment and change it out during planned shutdowns continues.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	With an average monthly power bill of approximately $4 million, Higginson believes that every opportunity to change out an old motor and replace it with a Reliance 841 XL means continued incremental improvements.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;Reducing the bill by several percentage points makes a big difference,&amp;rdquo; he says. &amp;ldquo;It also offers a dramatic return on our investment because when you couple the efficiency savings of this motor along with the energy rebates offered by our local utility, the payback for the motor is less than one year.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	In the end, the numbers on paper added up the same way on NORPAC&amp;rsquo;s mill floor. The scientific approach, the calculations developed and the recommendations made were right. Because of the work done by Holmquist and his technology team, NORPAC has cut energy and maintenance costs, reduced downtime and lowered its total cost of ownership.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	For more information, visit the Baldor Web site at &lt;a href="http://www.baldor.com/"&gt;www.baldor.com&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/motors/~4/j-_CFRrCKEw" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
            <a10:updated>2010-04-20T11:21:39-05:00</a10:updated>
            <a10:content type="text/html" src="http://reliableplant.com/Read/24119/motors-energy-dollars" />
        <feedburner:origLink>http://reliableplant.com/Read/24119/motors-energy-dollars</feedburner:origLink></item>
        <item>
            <guid isPermaLink="false">tag:noria.com,2010-06-10:publishing:magazines:rp:e6c4a0ff-3138-4e4b-8f48-9d5d009eaa87</guid>
            <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/motors/~3/X4zF61WVdBo/culligan-h2-inverter-bottling-operation</link>
            <a10:author>
                <a10:name>Baldor Electric Company</a10:name>
            </a10:author>
            <category>Web Exclusives</category>
            <category>Articles</category>
            <title>Culligan uses H2 inverter to improve its bottling operation</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	The Culligan name has become internationally famous. &amp;ldquo;Hey Culligan Man!&amp;rdquo; became a well-known phrase and the Culligan Water Treatment System has become a world leader. Culligan does more for business than provide softeners and treatment products. They&amp;rsquo;re also a leading distributor of bottled water and filtered drinking water systems for commercial and industrial use.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Culligan, located in Tulsa, Okla., is making good use of an H2 inverter from Baldor Electric Company. In this facility, Culligan bottles eight-ounce to five-gallon bottled water used by its commercial and industrial customers. A separate operation of this plant is the deionization/regeneration facility. In this area, backwash funnels are used and must hold a desired pressure. By using the PID function of the drive, the line operator never has to worry about having too much or too little water pressure. More importantly, the Baldor drive is able to deliver a steady water flow and pressure rate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;
	&lt;img src=" http://media.noria.com/sites/web_exclusives/Culligan001.jpg " /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Culligan&amp;rsquo;s vice president of operations, Chip Pearce, stated, &amp;ldquo;Before this new setup, we had to walk 300 feet back and forth to stop and start our motor, and the pressure in the pipe was only a &amp;lsquo;good guess&amp;rsquo;. It&amp;rsquo;s nice to see the automation of this part of our operation. I know the operator simply loves it.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	When the line operator shuts off all of the water valves, nothing is seen on his end. But 300 feet down line, the Baldor drive is seeing the demand drop to zero and knows to stop the motor and pump. Seeing no demand, the drive goes into a &amp;ldquo;sleep&amp;rdquo; mode. Later, when the operator opens the valve again and drops the pressure below the set point, the drive wakes back up and gives a command to the motor and pump to repressurize the pipe. This occurs in a seamless transition, allowing the operator to fill from one to 32 containers consistently and reliably, resulting in more productivity at the fill area and better service to the customer.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Duncan Industrial Solutions, suppliers of the pumping equipment, installed the drive, set all of the parameters and immediately could control the &amp;ldquo;stop and start&amp;rdquo; of the motor and pump.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	For more information on Baldor motors and drives, visit &lt;a href="http://www.baldor.com/"&gt;www.baldor.com&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/motors/~4/X4zF61WVdBo" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
